{"type":"message","id":"1941b065","parentId":"023256b2","timestamp":"2026-04-16T11:20:38.806Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the problem clearly:\n\n```\nEmbeddings: unavailable\nEmbeddings error: fetch failed\n```\n\nThe embeddings are unavailable because `fetch failed`. The provider is trying to use `openai` (text-embedding-3-small) but it can't reach the OpenAI API. This is because there's no API key configured for OpenAI in the memory search setup.\n\nBut wait, there's also this from the `memory-lancedb` config that was removed:\n```\n\"baseUrl\": \"http://172.23.96.1:11434/v1\"  # This was the Ollama endpoint\n```\n\nThe lancedb was pointing to Ollama at 172.23.96.1:11434. \n\nAfter removing lancedb, there's no embedding provider configured at all, so `memory_search` can't function. The `memory-core` plugin relies on embeddings for vector search, and with none configured, it can't reach OpenAI's API without an API key. I need to either set up an OpenAI embedding key or reconfigure Ollama as the embedding provider.\n\nLooking at the config changes, `memory-core` has `dreaming.enabled: true` but no embedding configuration, while the active memory is using the default `memorySearch` settings which attempt OpenAI and fail. I could configure `memorySearch` with an Ollama endpoint like `http://host.docker.internal:11434/v1` since we're on WSL2, or fall back to lexical-only search without embeddings. But actually, the main `memory_search` tool should work for Active Memory as long as it can return results—even in degraded mode without vectors, it might still function.\n\nNow I'm tracing through the actual error in the logs. The `sync failed (search-bootstrap)` error occurred during bootstrap, and the Active Memory agent also failed with a timeout after 16 seconds while trying to use `minimax/MiniMax-M2.7`. The timeout suggests the memory search is hanging rather than immediately failing, so I need to figure out why the MiniMax model call is stalling.\n\nThe issue is that memory search is trying to reach OpenAI's embedding endpoint but can't, which is causing the entire bootstrap process to hang. Once that connection fails, the Active Memory agent never gets the context it needs and times out waiting for a response. The `fetch failed` error from the `memory_search` call during bootstrap is the root cause—when that fails, the conversation context never gets built, so the agent has nothing to work with and just waits until the timeout kicks in.\n\nThe real problem is that `memorySearch` needs a proper embedding provider configured. Since the WSL2 environment can't directly reach external APIs, I should point it to a local Ollama instance instead, which is already available at `http://172.23.96.1:11434/v1` from the previous (now removed) lancedb configuration.","thinkingSignature":"b11eaa91ac6f310a614ef7169797ea4e4e18d011667c57c9387be9864b1486c7"},{"type":"text","text":"找到了。问题很清楚：\n\n```\nEmbeddings error: fetch failed\n```\n\n**根本原因**：memory search 的 embedding provider 试图调用 OpenAI API（没有 API key），加上 WSL2 网络无法直接访问外部 API，导致 fetch 全部失败。\n\n之前 memory-lancedb 残留配置里有一个本地 Ollama 地址（`172.23.96.1:11434`），删掉之后就什么都没有了。\n\n现在两条路：\n\n**方案 A**：配置 Ollama 本地 embedding（推荐，你有 Ollama）\n**方案 B**：改用纯 FTS 文本检索，不依赖 embedding\n\n先确认 Ollama 能不能联通：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_mbgycyq3nh52_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -s --connect-timeout 3 http://172.23.96.1:11434/api/tags 2>&1 | head -5"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_mbgycyq3nh52_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -s --connect-timeout 3 http://127.0.0.1:11434/api/tags 2>&1 | head -5"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":51273,"output":828,"cacheRead":21798,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":73899,"cost":{"input":0.015381899999999999,"output":0.0009935999999999999,"cacheRead":0.00130788,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.01768338}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776338416089,"responseId":"062ff8f03f6a97950fad08ecac8aabf4"}}
