{"type":"message","id":"98826b29","parentId":"d2205b4c","timestamp":"2026-04-16T11:47:38.142Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"gemma-3-4b took 16 seconds for a simple request! That's even slower than qwen2.5:14b (11s). And it gave \"有\" (yes) which is likely hallucination since the memory is empty.\n\nThis tells me the bottleneck is really the WSL2 network latency to the Ollama server at 172.23.96.1. The round-trip time is very long.\n\nWait, but the user previously had memory-lancedb configured with `baseUrl: \"http://172.23.96.1:11434/v1\"` and that was working (before I deleted it). \n\nSo Ollama was accessible before. The network latency shouldn't be the issue since curl calls to that address completed in under a second. But a full model inference round-trip through Ollama is taking 11-16 seconds, which suggests the inference itself is just inherently slow on this hardware.\n\nThe user has 9b and 14b parameter models running, and the reality is that even a simple 3-turn conversation with the model would take 30-50 seconds total. I've already tried switching to gemma-3-4b which is smaller but still took 16 seconds, so the bottleneck is the inference speed itself, not the model size. At this point, I need to accept that local inference with these models is too slow for Active Memory and either accept the latency or try a different approach entirely.\n\nWait—I just realized the lancedb setup was using that same Ollama instance at 172.23.96.1, and it was working fine. The difference is that lancedb was handling vector storage and retrieval locally, whereas Active Memory is making actual LLM inference calls through Ollama. The 172.23.96.1 address is the Windows host from WSL2, so Ollama is running on Windows with network access from WSL2. That's why vector lookups are fast but inference is slow—the inference is happening remotely on the Windows machine.\n\nLooking at the timing breakdown: the user's curl to Ollama took 11 seconds for a simple completion, but Active Memory is taking 25-30 seconds, which suggests it's making multiple inference calls within a single sub-agent run. I could try reducing the number of calls by switching to \"message\" mode or lowering max_tokens to make each call faster, but the real issue is that even with optimizations, the user needs to understand why this is happening. Let me explain the bottleneck and suggest the fastest possible configuration as a compromise.","thinkingSignature":"77e787a795d7c975d41740608e02da9393a756e010fc52518d550b575217fe06"},{"type":"text","text":"gemma-3-4b 更慢，16秒。结论很清楚了：\n\n**Ollama 推理本身就慢**（11-16秒一次），Active Memory sub-agent 要跑多步（搜 → 读 → 判断 → 汇总），叠加起来就是 25-30 秒。\n\n这个速度瓶颈来自 Ollama 推理本身，和模型大小关系不大（gemma-3-4b 最轻量也一样慢）。\n\n**能做的最优配置**——改 `queryMode: \"message\"` 减少 context 大小，同时限制 `max_tokens`，让单次推理最快：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_dvayv6487ywj_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 << 'EOF'\nimport json\n\npath = '/home/ai/.openclaw/openclaw.json'\nwith open(path) as f:\n    d = json.load(f)\n\ncfg = d['plugins']['entries']['active-memory']['config']\n# 切回 qwen2.5:14b（比 gemma 快）\ncfg['model'] = \"ollama/qwen2.5:14b\"\n# message 模式：只发当前消息，不发对话历史\ncfg['queryMode'] = \"message\"\n# 限制 token 上限，加快推理\ncfg['maxTokens'] = 50\n\nwith open(path, 'w') as f:\n    json.dump(d, f, indent=2, ensure_ascii=False)\n\nprint(json.dumps(cfg, indent=2))\nEOF"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":74212,"output":824,"cacheRead":18725,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":93761,"cost":{"input":0.022263599999999998,"output":0.0009888,"cacheRead":0.0011235,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0243759}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776340031462,"responseId":"062fff3e784596d0d442ee2a9e7b4366"}}
