{"type":"message","id":"2f30e80a","parentId":"c3103578","timestamp":"2026-04-16T12:09:31.721Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Load average is 1.29, memory is fine (12GB available). The system itself is not under heavy load.\n\nThe issue is likely something specific to the gateway or the agent. Let me look for any currently running agent tasks or embedded runs in the recent log.\n\nActually, I realize the sessions.list is slow because the gateway is busy running an agent task for the current user's session. When I ran sessions.list, it took a long time and returned sessions from an hour ago. The \"1h ago\" timestamps might mean those sessions haven't been updated in the last hour.\n\nWait - but the user is saying messages are slow. If an agent task is running for the user's session, the lane would be blocked and new messages would queue. \n\nSo the sessions with \"1h ago\" status are probably just sitting idle - those aren't blocking anything. If the user's channel shows as \"direct agent:fast_agent:main\" with \"1h ago\", that means the last message in that session was about an hour ago and it's not currently processing anything. But then why is sessions.list timing out? Maybe the actual bottleneck is just that MiniMax-M2.7 is inherently slow for generating responses, not a queuing issue.\n\nThe user's saying messages are slow to send, which could mean they're waiting for the gateway to receive and process them, or they're waiting for the AI response. If the Control UI is sending messages through the gateway to the agent and the agent is queued behind something, that would explain it. Or if the gateway is just slow at accepting the message. But maybe there isn't actually a queuing problem at all - maybe MiniMax-M2.7 itself is just slow. Though the user mentioned earlier that messages were fast before active-memory was added, which contradicts this.\n\nActually, the real bottleneck is probably just the AI model response time. 