{"type":"message","id":"a70609c0","parentId":"4c63645c","timestamp":"2026-04-16T12:14:18.564Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is saying they use localhost:3102 for both before and after upgrade. So the agent ID issue might be a red herring. Let me think about what else could be causing the slow messages.\n\nThe key question is: what changed between v2026.4.9 and v2026.4.14 that could cause messages to be slow?\n\nLooking at the changelog from earlier:\n- Active Memory (2026.4.10+)\n- Context Engine plugin slot (2026.4.10+)\n- Codex bundled provider (2026.4.10+)\n- LM Studio provider (2026.4.12+)\n- Telegram forum topics (2026.4.14)\n\n\n- OpenAI Codex forward-compat (2026.4.14)\n\nActive Memory was introduced in 2026.4.10 and we know it was causing slowness. Even though we removed the config, the plugin binary itself is still loaded in v2026.4.14 and could be running its hook on every message, whereas it wasn't present in v2026.4.9 at all.\n\nThe plugin is listed as loaded in the system, so it's active even without explicit configuration. It might have a `before_agent_reply` hook that intercepts every message, and if that hook is doing something like calling memory search, it could add overhead. Though a properly implemented hook shouldn't cause 25-second delays just from being registered—it would only do work if configured and enabled.\n\nBut wait, if the plugin was always there, maybe the real issue isn't the plugin itself. The user downgraded from 2026.4.14 to an earlier version, so the compiled binary would be different. The newer version might have introduced behavior that affects message handling, like how the model loading or initialization works during startup.\n\nActually, thinking about the startup process—the config change triggered a restart, and during that restart the gateway was briefly unavailable or slow to come back online. That could explain the perceived slowness in sending messages.\n\nBut the user said it was slow before they even made any config changes, right after the upgrade. So the issue isn't something I did—it started immediately after upgrading from 2026.4.9 to 2026.4.14. The downgrade to 2026.4.14 happened later, which means 2026.4.14 itself might be the culprit.\n\nThe changelog shows that Active Memory was introduced in 2026.4.10, so it didn't exist in 2026.4.9. That timing lines up perfectly with when the slowness started. Even if the user never explicitly configured Active Memory, it could be running by default or with some default settings that are causing the slowdown.\n\nI'm wondering if Active Memory is running on every single message by default now, regardless of configuration, and that's what's causing the delay between when the user sends a message and when it actually gets processed.\n\nLooking at the gateway logs, I'm not seeing any Active Memory entries after 19:43, which suggests it should be dormant. But the user said the slowness was happening right after upgrade and before any config changes. Let me reconsider what's actually happening here.\n\nWhen the user downgraded and removed the active-memory config, the gateway restarted and came back online. Now when they try to send a message through Control UI connected to localhost:3102, it's still slow. I'm noticing there's a difference between the old Control UI connection (conn=61b25d6e) and the new one (conn=66b7d058), which means a new WebSocket connection was established after the restart. The sessions.list calls are responding normally at 113ms, so the gateway itself is responsive, but something about how the message is being routed through this new connection might be the bottleneck.\n\nThe agent field in the request could be the issue—it's showing \"unknown agent id 'main'\" in the error, which suggests the request might be trying to use an agent that doesn't exist or isn't configured properly. Since I can't see the actual content of the inbound messages, I'm missing the key piece to diagnose what's happening with the message flow itself.\n\nBut wait—the user said the slowness started immediately after upgrading from 2026.4.9 to 2026.4.14, before I made any config changes. The only thing that changed was the OpenClaw version itself. The changelog shows that Active Memory was introduced in 2026.4.10, which came after 2026.4.9, so that's likely the culprit—something about how it was integrated in this version is causing the delay.\n\nI can't reproduce the old version easily, but I know Active Memory was doing blocking sub-agent calls that took 25+ seconds even when it had nothing to do. It was probably running by default even without explicit config. The fact that the user had to explicitly remove the config to stop it suggests it was enabled by default in 2026.4.14, which is a breaking change from 2026.4.9.\n\nSo the sequence is clear: upgrade to 2026.4.14 activates Active Memory, it runs a 25-second sub-agent on every message, messages get delayed. The fix was removing the config, but the user is still on 2026.4.14 without the problematic config. That should mean messages are fast now, unless something else changed in that version.\n\nActually, the user downgraded to 2026.4.14 and removed the config, but they're still on 2026.4.14. I already confirmed active-memory is gone from the config. So Active Memory shouldn't be running anymore. But they're saying messages are still slow. That doesn't make sense unless the issue is something else entirely.\n\nLet me check the gateway logs around 20:13 to see what's actually happening with messages, since I haven't seen any in the logs yet. The user is accessing via localhost:3102 through webchat, so the messages should be there.\n\nLooking back at the sessions list, the main agent session hasn't had activity in an hour, and when I look at recent activity, I'm only seeing Control UI connections and handshakes, no actual inbound messages from users. That suggests the user is either not sending messages right now, or their messages aren't being logged as inbound messages at all.\n\nSince the user says messages are still slow even after removing active-memory, the issue isn't that. Let me consider what's actually changed in version 2026.4.14 - the Codex forward-compatibility layer might be what's causing the slowdown if it's doing something on every message like checking capabilities or resolving models.\n\nI'm also wondering if the gateway restart itself is the culprit. When I removed the active-memory config and restarted, maybe the session state got corrupted or there's something about how the gateway reloaded that's causing delays on subsequent messages.\n\nThe user is being clear though - messages are still slow even after removing active-memory and restarting. So I need to figure out what's actually causing it. The thinking mode being set to adaptive might be relevant - I should check if that's a new setting in this version and whether it's affecting message processing speed.\n\nWait, the sessions output shows the agent is running adaptive thinking, but thinking is supposed to be per-request, not per-session. That's odd. More importantly, I'm noticing the `unknown agent id \"main\"` error in the logs - that could be the real issue. The gateway might be trying to route to an agent that doesn't exist, which would cause failures and apparent slowness. Let me look into whether that's what's happening.","thinkingSignature":"9919c72365fcddfa539b307dc23eee2fb7790bbc4e84d7e9828c81e828f1087f"},{"type":"text","text":"让我看更完整的请求日志，找出消息进来之后的完整链路：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_4eueatt88h77_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /tmp/openclaw/openclaw-2026-04-16.log | python3 -c \"\nimport sys, json\nlines = []\nfor line in sys.stdin:\n    try:\n        d = json.loads(line)\n        t = d.get('time','')\n        if t >= '2026-04-16T20:11' and t <= '2026-04-16T20:14':\n            lines.append((t, d))\n    except:\n        pass\nfor t, d in lines:\n    msg = str(d.get('1', d.get('0','')))[:120]\n    print(t[:19], msg)\n\" 2>&1 | head -60"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":58,"output":1725,"cacheRead":21798,"cacheWrite":81445,"totalTokens":105026,"cost":{"input":0.0000174,"output":0.00207,"cacheRead":0.00130788,"cacheWrite":0.030541875,"total":0.033937155}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776341594487,"responseId":"06300559c8509ab97528b6435588fdcc"}}
