{"type":"message","id":"94b27021","parentId":"8ad26080","timestamp":"2026-04-16T12:24:11.812Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still nothing. There are genuinely no inbound message logs from 20:16 onwards. But the user IS sending messages - we can see them in this very conversation. The messages are coming through to ME, but through a different channel/mechanism.\n\nWait - the messages I'm receiving have the label \"openclaw-control-ui\". This means they ARE going through the Control UI somehow. But gateway logs don't show chat.send...\n\nActually, I need to think about this differently. The messages I'm receiving from the user - they have the same metadata label \"openclaw-control-ui\". This conversation IS the evidence that messages are being sent and received. But gateway logs don't show them.\n\nThis could mean one of two things:\n1. The messages bypass the gateway entirely somehow (unlikely)\n2. The gateway IS receiving them but under a different event type that I haven't been grepping for\n\nLet me look at ALL log entries between 20:16 and now, filtering only for non-timeout, non-sessions.list entries to see if there's anything else.\n\n\nActually, I'm realizing the session ID for this conversation (delta-meadow, keen-harbor etc.) doesn't match the connection IDs I'm seeing in the logs (4580a98e). That's the Control UI connection, so my messages must be coming through a different connection. But wait - the user is definitely using the Control UI since the label says \"openclaw-control-ui\". The messages are clearly marked with that label, so they're coming through somehow.\n\nLooking at the logs more carefully, I notice the sessions.list calls are coming in at regular intervals from conn=4580a98e, which is the Control UI connection. But there's no corresponding chat.send request logged, which is strange. The messages must be arriving through a different mechanism than what I'm expecting to see in the logs.\n\nActually, thinking about this differently - my responses ARE going back through the Control UI connection, as evidenced by the ⇄ res responses logged. So the bidirectional communication is happening. The user's messages should be logged as incoming ⇄ req events if they're truly coming through the gateway. The fact that I'm not seeing them suggests either the gateway isn't logging incoming messages the way I expect, or there's filtering happening at the logging level. Let me reconsider whether the messages are even going through the gateway at all.\n\nWait - the user is clearly using the Control UI based on the metadata, and I'm receiving their messages and responding through the same channel. The fact that my responses are visible in the conversation proves the path works in both directions. If the user is seeing delays when sending messages but I'm receiving them normally, the bottleneck has to be on the gateway's response side - the chat.send call that carries my reply back to them. That's where the delay would be happening.\n\nLooking at the logs, I see one chat.send from 19:04 but nothing recent, which is odd. Either my responses aren't actually reaching the gateway, or they're failing silently without being logged. The issue might be with how the gateway logs chat.send responses or how my replies are being routed back through ws://localhost:3102/ to the Control UI.\n\nThe user's description is telling - they click send and wait before seeing their message appear in the input box, which suggests the bottleneck isn't the LLM generating responses but the message actually being registered by the system. If their message isn't reaching the gateway at all, that's the problem.\n\nLooking at the gateway logs, there's a massive gap - nothing from 20:04 to 20:11. Then after restart, the Control UI reconnects successfully at 20:11:16 with the right version (2026.4.14), but the session list is immediately throwing an \"unknown agent id\" error. That's the real issue - something about the session state after restart is broken, preventing messages from being processed properly.\n\nThe session is actually there in the logs from the session list output, so the ID exists. But the commands.list call fails with \"unknown agent id \"main\"\". In v2026.4.14, the Control UI might be validating that \"main\" is a registered agent before allowing anything to proceed. Let me look at what the current agents configuration actually has set up.\n\nThe configuration only lists fast_agent and deep_agent, but the workspace files are in `workspace/main/` and the session data shows sessions for agent \"main\" with fast_agent workspaces. There's also `agent:fast_agent:main` showing up in the logs, which suggests fast_agent is being treated as the default when \"main\" isn't found. The sessions might still be routed through fast_agent with the name \"main\", but the actual agent ID is fast_agent, which could be why the Control UI is rejecting it.\n\nThe real issue is that \"main\" was added back to agents.list with workspace `workspace/main`, but the sessions themselves are stored under `~/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/` while the workspace files are in `workspace/main/`. This mismatch between where sessions are stored versus where the agent definition points could be causing the gateway to not properly recognize the \"main\" agent when commands come in.\n\nThe user's actual problem is that messages are taking time to appear after sending—this could be a UI rendering delay where the Control UI isn't immediately displaying sent messages, or the message submission itself is slow. Since the gateway is running and receiving requests fine, the bottleneck is likely on the frontend side where messages sit in a pending state before being sent to the gateway. The fact that my responses ARE visible despite the gateway logs not showing recent message sends is telling - either my responses are coming through a different channel, or the logs are being truncated. Let me check the log file size and rotation settings to see if older entries are being purged.\n\nRather than continuing to dig through logs, I should focus on what the user actually needs: fixing the delay in message sends. The `commands.list` error for the unknown agent \"main\" is the most concrete issue I've found and likely the culprit.\n","thinkingSignature":"b7e52e2ece98406b989726dc362bb8151fb9b6257b884a4b434aeaecf2f9191a"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n好，我不再被动等日志，直接从根源查。最关键的错误是 `unknown agent id \"main\"` — 我已经加了 main 到 agents.list，但还要确认 gateway 真的在用它：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_490d97c1096f48f38171629d","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat ~/.openclaw/openclaw.json | python3 -c \"\nimport json,sys\nd=json.load(sys.stdin)\nprint('agents.list:', json.dumps(d['agents']['list'], indent=2))\nprint()\nprint('defaults model primary:', d['agents']['defaults']['model']['primary'])\n\" 2>&1"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_772402d0f7794aebabfbd10d","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /tmp/openclaw/openclaw-2026-04-16.log | grep -E \"20:16|20:17|20:18|20:19|20:20|20:21|20:22\" | grep -v \"sessions.list\\|chat.history\\|handshake timeout\" | python3 -c \"\nimport sys, json\nfor line in sys.stdin:\n    try:\n        d = json.loads(line)\n        t = d.get('time','')[:19]\n        msg = str(d.get('1', d.get('0','')))[:130]\n        print(t, msg)\n    except:\n        print(line.strip()[:130])\n\" 2>&1 | head -40"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":265,"output":1505,"cacheRead":114944,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":116714,"cost":{"input":0.0000795,"output":0.0018059999999999999,"cacheRead":0.006896639999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.008782139999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776342222601,"responseId":"063007cd947156e7488523e2cba724b9"}}
